 {"id":"wa-1i6d","title":"Process Tree Capture Per Pane","description":"## Goal
Capture the full process tree per pane (not just foreground process) for accurate session restoration, since AI agents spawn subprocesses that are critical to their operation.

## Background & Motivation
wa-32z7 (Process Re-launch) captures the foreground process per pane. But AI agents typically have deeper process trees:
```
pane 7:
  bash (shell)
    +-- claude (Claude Code CLI)
        +-- node (language server)
        +-- cargo check (compilation)
        +-- git status (version control)
```

If we only capture "claude" as the foreground process and restart it, the subprocesses are lost. The agent will restart but may be confused about the state of its subprocesses.

More importantly, the process tree reveals the agent's CURRENT ACTIVITY — if cargo is running, the agent is compiling; if git is running, it's checking version control. This information is valuable for snapshot decisions.

## Technical Design

### Process Tree Capture
```rust
pub struct ProcessTree {
    pub root: ProcessNode,
    pub total_processes: usize,
    pub total_threads: usize,
    pub total_rss_kb: u64,
}

pub struct ProcessNode {
    pub pid: u32,
    pub ppid: u32,
    pub name: String,
    pub cmdline: Vec<String>,
    pub state: ProcessState,  // Running, Sleeping, Zombie, etc.
    pub rss_kb: u64,
    pub cpu_time_ms: u64,
    pub children: Vec<ProcessNode>,
}
```

### Platform Implementation
Linux (/proc filesystem):
```rust
fn capture_process_tree(root_pid: u32) -> Result<ProcessTree> {
    // Read /proc/<pid>/stat for process info
    // Read /proc/<pid>/cmdline for command line
    // Read /proc/<pid>/status for RSS
    // Recursively walk /proc/<pid>/task/<tid>/children
    // Build tree from parent-child relationships
}
```

macOS (sysctl + libproc):
```rust
fn capture_process_tree_macos(root_pid: u32) -> Result<ProcessTree> {
    // Use proc_listchildpids() for children
    // Use proc_pidinfo() for process details
}
```

### Integration with Snapshot Schema
Extend PaneSnapshot (from bd-cuz) with process_tree field:
```rust
pub struct PaneSnapshot {
    // ... existing fields ...
    pub foreground_process: ProcessInfo,
    pub process_tree: Option<ProcessTree>,  // NEW
}
```

### Activity Inference from Process Tree
```rust
fn infer_activity(tree: &ProcessTree) -> PaneActivity {
    // If cargo/rustc running → Compiling
    // If git running → Version control
    // If npm/node running → JavaScript tooling
    // If python running → Script execution
    // If no children → Idle/waiting for input
}
```

This feeds into the priority classifier (wa-1qz1.5) as additional evidence.

### Implementation Location
- New: crates/wa-core/src/process_tree.rs
- Modify: snapshot schema (bd-cuz PaneSnapshot)
- Integration: ingest.rs captures tree periodically (every 30s, not every poll)

## Existing Code References
- bd-cuz: PaneSnapshot, ProcessInfo (extend with tree)
- wa-32z7: Process re-launch (uses tree for better restore)
- ingest.rs: capture pipeline (periodic tree capture)

## Configuration
```toml
[process_tree]
enabled = true
capture_interval_secs = 30    # How often to capture tree
max_depth = 5                 # Maximum tree depth
include_threads = false       # Include thread info (expensive)
```

## Dependencies
- bd-cuz (snapshot schema): extend PaneSnapshot
- Enhances wa-32z7 (process re-launch): more accurate restore
- Enhances wa-1qz1.5 (evidence ledger): activity inference as evidence

## Acceptance Criteria
- Full process tree capture per pane on Linux and macOS
- Process tree included in snapshots
- Activity inference from process tree
- Configurable capture frequency and depth
- Unit tests: mock /proc filesystem, verify tree construction
- Integration test: capture tree for real agent process

## macOS Platform Note
Process tree traversal must use platform-specific APIs:
- **Linux**: reads `/proc/<pid>/stat` for process info, `/proc/<pid>/cmdline` for command line, `/proc/<pid>/status` for RSS, and recursively walks `/proc/<pid>/task/<tid>/children` for child discovery.
- **macOS**: use `proc_pidinfo(pid, PROC_PIDLISTCHILDREN, ...)` or `proc_listchildpids(pid, ...)` from `libproc.h` to enumerate child processes. For process details, use `proc_pidinfo(pid, PROC_PIDTASKINFO, ...)` to get `proc_taskinfo` (RSS via `pti_resident_size`, CPU time via `pti_total_user + pti_total_system`). For command line, use `proc_pidinfo(pid, PROC_PIDPATHINFO, ...)` for the executable path and `sysctl([CTL_KERN, KERN_PROCARGS2, pid])` for full argv. As a simpler fallback, `pgrep -P <pid>` provides child PID enumeration without requiring FFI bindings.

## Benchmark Requirements
- **criterion benchmarks** with target `benches/process_tree.rs`:
  - `tree_traversal_latency`: measure time to capture the full process tree for a root PID with 5-20 children at depth 1-3. Target: <5ms for a typical agent process tree (shell + agent + 10 subprocesses).
  - `tree_serialization`: measure time to serialize ProcessTree to the snapshot format. Target: <100us for a 20-node tree.
  - `activity_inference`: measure time to classify activity from a process tree. Target: <10us per tree (simple pattern matching on process names).

## Property-Based Testing (proptest)
- **Tree consistency**: for any captured ProcessTree, every child node's `ppid` matches its parent's `pid`. The tree structure is always valid (no orphan nodes, no cycles).
- **Idempotent capture**: capturing the same process tree twice in quick succession (within 100ms) produces structurally identical trees (same PIDs, same parent-child relationships), assuming no process churn.
- **Depth limiting**: when `max_depth = D`, no node in the captured tree has depth > D. Deeper processes are silently omitted, not errored.
- **RSS aggregation**: `tree.total_rss_kb == sum of node.rss_kb for all nodes in tree`. The aggregate is always consistent with individual node values.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-02-09T22:43:48.307582Z","created_by":"jemanuel","updated_at":"2026-02-10T23:19:05.107616-05:00","closed_at":"2026-02-10T23:19:05.107616-05:00","close_reason":"Process tree capture implemented: ProcessTree/ProcessNode types, Linux /proc parser, macOS ps-based safe capture, PaneActivity inference from tree contents. 23 tests passing.","dependencies":[{"issue_id":"wa-1i6d","depends_on_id":"wa-rsaf","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-02-09T22:45:31.464399Z","created_by":"jemanuel"},{"issue_id":"wa-1i6d","depends_on_id":"wa-rbvl","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-02-09T22:45:52.300245Z","created_by":"jemanuel"},{"issue_id":"wa-1i6d","depends_on_id":"wa-cuz","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-02-09T22:45:52.300245Z","created_by":"jemanuel"}]}
-{"id":"wa-1igc","title":"Safe-restart workflow — atomic snapshot-restart-restore cycle","description":"## Goal
Implement the atomic safe-restart workflow that coordinates: snapshot save, mux server stop, mux server start, snapshot restore, with rollback on failure.

## Background and Motivation
This is the crown jewel of the session persistence system -- the single command that makes mux server restarts safe. Currently, restarting the mux server is catastrophic (kills all 50+ agent sessions). This workflow makes it a routine maintenance operation.

The workflow must be atomic: if any step fails, it should roll back or at least leave the system in a known state. It must also handle the inherent race condition: after saving the snapshot but before stopping the mux server, new output may arrive in panes.

## Technical Design

### Command
```
wa restart [--timeout <seconds>] [--skip-restore] [--label <label>] [--launch-agents]
```

### Workflow Steps
```rust
pub async fn safe_restart(&self, config: RestartConfig) -> Result<RestartReport> {
    let mut report = RestartReport::new();

    // Phase 1: Pre-flight checks
    report.phase("preflight");
    self.verify_mux_server_running().await?;
    self.verify_snapshot_config().await?;
    let pane_count = self.count_active_panes().await?;
    info!("Pre-flight: {} active panes", pane_count);

    // Phase 2: Snapshot
    report.phase("snapshot");
    let snapshot = self.engine
        .capture_snapshot(SnapshotTrigger::PreRestart).await?;
    report.snapshot_id = Some(snapshot.id.clone());
    info!("Snapshot saved: {} ({} panes)", snapshot.id, pane_count);

    // Phase 3: Stop mux server
    report.phase("stop");
    self.stop_mux_server(config.timeout).await?;
    self.verify_mux_server_stopped().await?;
    info!("Mux server stopped");

    // Phase 4: Start mux server
    report.phase("start");
    self.start_mux_server().await?;
    self.wait_for_mux_ready(Duration::from_secs(10)).await?;
    info!("Mux server started and ready");

    // Phase 5: Restore (unless --skip-restore)
    if !config.skip_restore {
        report.phase("restore");
        let restore_result = self.restore_snapshot(&snapshot, &config).await;
        match restore_result {
            Ok(restore_report) => {
                report.restore = Some(restore_report);
                info!("Restoration complete");
            }
            Err(e) => {
                warn!("Restoration failed: {}. Snapshot {} available for manual restore.",
                    e, snapshot.id);
                report.restore_error = Some(e.to_string());
            }
        }
    }

    Ok(report)
}
```

### Rollback Strategy
- If snapshot fails: abort entirely, mux server unchanged
- If mux stop fails: abort, snapshot saved for future use
- If mux start fails: CRITICAL -- log snapshot ID prominently, user must fix manually
- If restore fails: NOT fatal -- snapshot exists, user can wa snapshot restore manually

### Mux Server Control
```rust
async fn stop_mux_server(&self, timeout: Duration) -> Result<()> {
    let pid = self.find_mux_server_pid()?;
    signal::kill(Pid::from_raw(pid), Signal::SIGTERM)?;
    let deadline = Instant::now() + timeout;
    while Instant::now() < deadline {
        if !self.is_process_running(pid) {
            return Ok(());
        }
        tokio::time::sleep(Duration::from_millis(100)).await;
    }
    Err(Error::MuxServerStopTimeout)
}

async fn start_mux_server(&self) -> Result<()> {
    Command::new("wezterm-mux-server")
        .arg("--daemonize")
        .spawn()?;
    Ok(())
}
```

## Safety Design
- Snapshot is ALWAYS saved before any destructive action
- Snapshot ID is prominently logged at every step
- Even if restore fails, the snapshot persists in SQLite
- The command can be re-run with wa snapshot restore for manual recovery
- No --force flag -- this workflow is inherently careful

## Integration Points
- SnapshotEngine: Save snapshot
- Layout/scrollback/process restorers: Full restoration
- wa process management: Start/stop mux server
- wa event bus: Emit restart lifecycle events

## Key Files to Create/Modify
- CREATE: crates/wa-core/src/snapshot/restart.rs
- MODIFY: crates/wa/src/commands/snapshot.rs (add restart subcommand)
- MODIFY: crates/wa-core/src/snapshot/mod.rs

## Dependencies
- CLI commands (bead 9) -- integrates with wa snapshot subcommand structure

## Acceptance Criteria
- Full restart cycle completes successfully with 50+ panes
- Snapshot is saved before any destructive action
- Mux server restarts cleanly (old process stopped, new one started)
- Layout, scrollback, and processes restored after restart
- Failure at any phase is handled gracefully with clear error messages
- Snapshot ID prominently displayed for manual recovery
- Total restart time < 30 seconds for 50 panes (excluding process re-launch)

## Estimated Effort
3-4 hours implementation, 2 hours testing

## macOS Process Management Notes
On macOS, process management differs from Linux in several ways:
- **PID file location**: The WezTerm mux server PID file is typically at XDG_RUNTIME_DIR/wezterm/pid on Linux, but on macOS XDG_RUNTIME_DIR is not standard. Check TMPDIR/wezterm-uid/pid or ~/Library/Application Support/wezterm/pid as fallbacks.
- **Process existence check**: On Linux, kill(pid, 0) works for process existence checks. On macOS this also works, but additionally use sysctl CTL_KERN/KERN_PROC for more reliable process existence verification when the process is not owned by the current user.
- **Daemonization**: wezterm-mux-server --daemonize works on both platforms, but on macOS you may also need to handle launchd integration for auto-start after restart.
- **Signal handling**: SIGTERM behavior is identical on both platforms, but on macOS the mux server may take longer to shut down if it has open PTYs (macOS PTY cleanup is slower than Linux). Adjust the default timeout accordingly (15s on macOS vs 10s on Linux).

```rust
fn default_stop_timeout() -> Duration {
    if cfg!(target_os = "macos") {
        Duration::from_secs(15)
    } else {
        Duration::from_secs(10)
    }
}
```

## Test Requirements

### Concurrency Testing (LabRuntime DPOR)
Use LabRuntime with Dynamic Partial Order Reduction to verify concurrent restart coordination:
- Verify that two concurrent wa restart invocations never both proceed past the snapshot phase (mutual exclusion via lock file or atomic flag)
- Verify that a periodic snapshot and a restart snapshot do not conflict (the restart must wait for or cancel the periodic snapshot)
- Verify that the stop-start sequence is atomic: no other wa command can observe the mux server in a partially-stopped state
- Verify that if Phase 4 (start) fails, no restore is attempted and the snapshot ID is preserved for manual recovery
- Verify that concurrent wa snapshot restore and wa restart do not interleave their layout restoration steps

### Criterion Benchmarks
Add benchmarks in crates/wa-core/benches/restart_workflow.rs:
- bench_full_restart_cycle_10_panes: Full snapshot-stop-start-restore cycle with 10 panes (mocked mux server), target <5s
- bench_full_restart_cycle_50_panes: Same with 50 panes, target <15s
- bench_preflight_checks: Pre-flight verification (mux running, config valid, pane count), target <100ms
- bench_mux_readiness_poll: Time from mux server start to accepting connections

### Property-Based Testing (proptest)
Add proptest cases in crates/wa-core/tests/proptest_restart.rs:
- **Atomic restart state machine**: Model the restart as a state machine (Idle -> Snapshotting -> Stopping -> Starting -> Restoring -> Complete/Failed). For any sequence of injected failures at each phase transition, verify the system ends in a valid terminal state (Complete or a specific Failed-at-phase state) and never in an intermediate state. Strategy: arb_failure_injection() generates Option of Error for each of the 5 phase transitions.
- **Rollback consistency**: For any failure point, verify that: (a) if failure is before snapshot, mux server is unchanged; (b) if failure is after snapshot, the snapshot ID is recoverable; (c) if failure is after stop, the start is still attempted (best-effort recovery).
- **Config validation**: For any RestartConfig (random timeout in [1s, 600s], random boolean flags), the workflow must either complete or fail with a meaningful error -- never panic. Strategy: arb_restart_config() generates random configs.","status":"in_progress","priority":1,"issue_type":"feature","assignee":"DustyBay","created_at":"2026-02-09T19:33:40.219368Z","created_by":"jemanuel","updated_at":"2026-03-31T03:11:51.011259Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"wa-1igc","depends_on_id":"ft-15fy","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-02-09T19:35:40.390036Z","created_by":"jemanuel","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"wa-1igc","depends_on_id":"wa-rsaf","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-02-09T19:35:07.906019Z","created_by":"jemanuel","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}],"comments":[{"id":2626,"issue_id":"wa-1igc","author":"BrightCliff","text":"Picking up the currently stale in-progress safe-restart bead. Investigation found ft restart and ft snapshot restore are already wired in the CLI, but restore mode is incomplete: restore_snapshot_checkpoint ignores --layout-only and SessionRestorer defines restore_scrollback without using it. I am taking the contained integration slice: wire scrollback-vs-layout-only behavior through restore, add regression tests, and update session-persistence docs to match the implemented surfaces.","created_at":"2026-03-30T22:14:40Z"},{"id":2627,"issue_id":"wa-1igc","author":"BrightCliff","text":"Implemented the restore-phase wiring slice: SessionRestorer now loads persisted scrollback references from mux_pane_state, can replay output_segments into restored panes when restore_scrollback is enabled, and emits scrollback stats/errors in RestoreSummary. CLI restore/restart now map --layout-only to restore_scrollback=false instead of ignoring the flag, and the session-persistence docs/AGENTS note were updated to match the real surfaces. Remote verification is in progress via rch; the new 